{{Infobox NRHP | name = Magnolia Cemetery including Mobile National Cemetery | image = Mobile National Cemetery.JPG | caption = A portion of Mobile National Cemetery. | lat_degrees = 30 | lat_minutes = 40 | lat_seconds = 22 | lat_direction = N | long_degrees = 88 | long_minutes = 03 | long_seconds = 45 | long_direction = W | locmapin = Alabama#USA | location = [[Mobile, Alabama]] | built = 1866 | architecture = | added = 13 June 1986 <ref name= nris/> | area = {{convert|91|acre}} | governing_body = Local<!--National Cemetery Administration--> | refnum = 86003757<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref><ref name="NRHP"|>{{cite web|title=Alabama - Mobile County|work="Nationalhistoricalregister.com"| url=http://www.nationalhistoricalregister.com/al/Mobile/state2.html|accessdate=2007-11-18}}</ref> }} '''Mobile National Cemetery''' is a [[United States National Cemetery]] located in the city of [[Mobile, Alabama]]. It encompasses {{convert|5.2|acre}}, and as of the end of 2005, had 5,326 interments. It is an annex to the larger [[Magnolia Cemetery (Mobile, Alabama)|Magnolia Cemetery]].<ref name="sledge">Sledge, John Sturdivant. ''Cities of Silence: A Guide to Mobile's Historic Cemeteries'', pages 24-26. Tuscaloosa, Alabama: University of Alabama Press, 2002.</ref> Mobile National Cemetery is administered by [[Barrancas National Cemetery]] in [[Pensacola, Florida]], and is currently closed to new interments.<ref name="natcemetery">{{cite web|title=Mobile National Cemetery|work="U.S. Department of Veteran Affairs"|url=http://www.cem.va.gov/CEM/cems/nchp/mobile.asp#hi|accessdate=2007-11-27}}</ref>
== History == Mobile National Cemetery was established in 1865, when [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] troops occupied the city of Mobile after the [[Battle of Mobile Bay]], during the [[American Civil War|Civil War]].<ref name="natcemetery"/> Initially, casualties of the battle were interred in a section of the city owned [[Magnolia Cemetery (Mobile, Alabama)|Magnolia Cemetery]], but they quickly had a need for more space and a plot of {{convert|3|acre}} was granted to the [[United States Army|Army]] by the city in 1866.<ref name="natcemetery"/> By 1871, the cemetery had 841 interments, mostly soldiers whose remains were moved from other nearby battlefield sites.<ref name="natcemetery"/>
Mobile National Cemetery was listed, along with the rest of [[Magnolia Cemetery (Mobile, Alabama)|Magnolia Cemetery]], on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on 13 June 1986.<ref name=nris/>
== Notable monuments == * The 76th Illinois Volunteer Infantry Regiment Monument was erected in 1892 by the survivors of the [[Battle of Fort Blakely]].<ref name="natcemetery"/> * The Confederate Fortification Monument, a granite monument, was erected by the [[United Daughters of the Confederacy]] in 1940.<ref name="natcemetery"/>
== Notable interments == * Private First Class [[John Dury New]], [[Medal of Honor]] recipient for action in [[World War II]].<ref>{{FAG|7130040|John Dury New}}</ref>
